This section explains how the main system components interact to support key user goals. The interactions below are directly linked to Story 2, Story 4 and Story 5 and their associated acceptance criteria. Each interaction demonstrates how the proposed architecture (UI, backend, database and supporting modules) supports the required behaviours.

Diagram 1 – Recording Daily Food Intake

This interaction supports Story 2: Kieran – Track Daily Food Intake. The authenticated user submits a food entry containing meal type and calorie value. The UI sends this data to the backend, where validation checks are performed before storage. The backend ensures required fields are present and calorie inputs are numeric and non-negative. If validation fails, submission is rejected and the UI prompts correction. If valid, the entry is stored in the database with a timestamp.
Daily totals are calculated dynamically by retrieving all entries for that date and aggregating them. This ensures edits or deletions immediately update the summary without storing redundant totals. This interaction shows clear separation of concerns: the UI collects and displays data, the backend handles validation and logic, and the database stores timestamped entries only.

Diagram 2 – Viewing Progress Over Time
This interaction supports Story 4: Leonard – Track Progress Over Time. When Leonard accesses the progress view, the backend retrieves timestamped entries for the selected date range. If insufficient data exists, the system returns a clear message, satisfying the acceptance criteria. If sufficient data exists, the backend aggregates the records and returns a structured dataset to the UI, where the visualisation module renders a time-based graph. 
Trend data is calculated dynamically rather than stored, reducing redundancy and maintaining consistency. Secure transmission and encrypted storage support the relevant non-functional requirements, while performance constraints ensure graphs render within the required timeframe.

Diagram 3 – Viewing Friend Rankings
This interaction supports Story 5: Olivia – Compare Progress With Friends. When Olivia opens the ranking view, the backend verifies authentication and retrieves accepted friends.If no friends exist, a structured message is returned explaining that rankings require connections. If friends exist, recent activity data is retrieved and passed to the ranking module, which calculates the leaderboard dynamically. 
Weekly workout count is used as the default ranking metric, in line with the acceptance criteria, with optional additional modes available. The sorted leaderboard is returned to the UI for display. Restricting queries to accepted friends and defined time ranges supports both privacy and performance requirements.

Diagram 4 – Ranking Update After Logging Activity
This interaction supports Story 5: This interaction shows how activity logging integrates with the ranking system. When a new workout is recorded, the entry is validated and stored as described in Story 2. When the ranking view is refreshed, the leaderboard is recalculated dynamically using updated activity data. Ranking positions are not permanently stored, reducing inconsistency and supporting scalability.
